solutions.content:
Here we simply calculate the shift required for each character of ```s``` and and store it in an array of size 26. Then check if those many shift are possible or not within the given value of ```k```.
* ```ar[i] = x``` implies that there are x characters in ```string s``` that need a shift of i to match the charcters in ```string t```.
* Now it is given in the question that each shift can be used only once. 
* So if two charcters need a shift of 1, only one of them will be allowed.
* The next charcter will get a shift of 1 + 26 which makes the efective shift to be 1. 
Eg: lets say ```s = "aa"``` and ```t = "cc"```
Then ```ar[2] = 2```
So two characters need a net shift of 2. So the possible shifts are 2, 28, 54, .....
Since we need only two, so 2 and 28 are enough. Therefore our value of k should be atleast 28 .If not then return false immediately.

```
class Solution {
public:
    bool canConvertString(string s, string t, int k) {
        if(s.length() != t.length()) return false;
        int ar[26] = {0};       
        for(int i = 0;i < s.length();i++){
            int shift = (t[i] - s[i] + 26) % 26;            
            ar[shift]++;
        }
        for(int i = 1;i <= 25;i++)
            if(i + (ar[i] - 1)*26 > k)
                return false;
        return true;        
    }
};
```

