# Intuition
We can convert *s* to *t* only if for every position *i* (*0 <= i < s.size()*) where *s[i] != t[i]* we can find a unique number *1 <= n <= k* such that *s[i] + (n % 26)  == t[i]*. (26 is the number of characters in english alphabet).

# Approach
First we check sizes of the two strings. When they differ, we return false immidiately. Next, we iterate over the strings and count only chars that do differ. When difference is negative, we add 26 to it.

In the last step, we iterate over the summery map and check every position, where difference greater than 0. For example, when we have a difference 2 in 3 positions, we have to use numbers 2, 28 and 54 to close gaps in all three positions (2, 2 + 1 x 26, 2 + 2 x 26). When the maximal number do not exceeds k, we return true, otherwise false. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
- O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:
- O(n)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
	const int alphabet_size = 26;

public:
	bool canConvertString(string s, string t, int k) {
		if (s.size() != t.size()) {
			return false;
		}
		vector<int> movesMap(127, 0);
		for (int i = 0; i < s.size(); i++) {
			int diff = t[i] - s[i];
			if (diff > 0) {
				movesMap[diff]++;
			}
			else if (diff < 0) {
				movesMap[alphabet_size + diff]++;
			}
		}
		if (movesMap.empty()) {
			return true;
		}

		for (int i = 0; i < movesMap.size(); i++) {
			if ((movesMap[i] > 0) && (i + (movesMap[i] - 1) * alphabet_size > k)) {
				return false;
			}
		}
		return true;
	}
};
```

