# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Similar to question 921

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Walk through every parantheses in input string and use two variable **insertion** and **right_need** to record the status of parantheses need.
- **Insertion** record the number of insertion activities needed before current char
- **right_need** record the number of right parantheses need
***

## Cases
1. If current char is '('
    * We need two more right parantheses: 
        * right_need +=2
    * If current right_need is odd, the pattern is invalid. Thus, we need to insert one ')' 
        * insertion++, right_need--
2. If current char is ')'
    * The right paranthesis we need would minus one 
    * If the right_need is -1, it means there is a extra right paranthesis. To match the pattern '())', we insert one left paranthesis and need one more right paranthesis.


# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(1)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minInsertions(string s) {
        int insertion=0;
        int right_need=0;
        for(char c: s){
            if(c=='('){
                right_need+=2;
                if(right_need%2==1){
                    insertion++;
                    right_need--;
                }
            }
            else if(c==')'){
                right_need--;
                if(right_need==-1){
                    right_need=1;
                    insertion++;
                }

            }
        }
        return insertion+right_need;
    }
};
```

