# Intuition
Want to use a bitmask to subsitute a dictionary because our alphabet is a fixed length (the numebr of digits "0-9" = 10 digits). Similar to Prefix Sum + Hashmap Medium problems, but with a bitmask spin to get lower time and space complexity. 

# Approach
Read in-text comments

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(N) for the outer for loop and O(10) for inner for loop = O(10 * N) = O(N)

- Space complexity:
O(1), because of bitmask

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int longestAwesome(String s) {
        int ans = 0;
        // Mask = 0b0000000000 -> There are 10 zeroes because we have 10 possible vals 0-9 as our alphabet
        // 0th place is 1 if we have odd number of 0s and 0 if we have even number of 0s
        // 1th place is 1 ... 
        int mask = 0;

        HashMap<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap();
        map.put(0, -1);

        for (int idx = 0; idx < s.length(); idx++) {
            // lets say s.charAt(idx) == 3. We shift 0b1 by 3 so that we get 0b1000
            // lets say mask = 0b1000 -> the xOr will evaluate to 0b000
            // This means we had an odd number of 3s now we have an even number of all values
            mask ^= 1 << (s.charAt(idx) - '0');


            // If we see matching masks then that means the number of odd characters 
            // and those corresponding characters that are odd are the same
            // Substracting one substring from another we get a new susbtring with no odd freq characters
            if (map.containsKey(mask)) {
                ans = Math.max(ans, idx - map.get(mask));
            } else {
                map.put(mask, idx);
            }

            // Palindrome can also have 1 character with an odd freq (in the middle)
            for (int shift = 0; shift < 10; shift++) {
                // Consider all masks that differ by mask in 1 place
                int oddMask = mask ^ (1 << shift);

                if (map.containsKey(oddMask)) {
                    ans = Math.max(ans, idx - map.get(oddMask));
                }
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
}
```

