cnt(j) --> number of occurences of j, till ith index.
cur_state --> string to represent the current state.

cur_state(j) ->0 ==> j appears an even number of times till ith index.
cur_state(j) ->1 ==> j appears an odd number of times till ith index.

Let cur_state for any arbitary index i = "0100000000"
This means that 1 has appeared an odd number of times, till ith index and all other digits appeared 
0 number of times.

Since we want to find longest substring, for which the substring could be rearranged to a palindrome .
This is possible in 2 cases
case 1: if all the distinct characters in the substring appears an even number of time
case 2: if all the distinct characters in the substring appears an even number of time, except for one character.

any state that we encouter is stored in a hash map against the index where that state occured, if the same state  or a state such that only one index is altered occurs later in the traversal ==> the substring between them including the cur index and not including the prev index is a valid answer.
Just find the maximum length among all such valid answers.

``
class Solution {
public:
    int longestAwesome(string s) {

        unordered_map<string, int>mp; // (state, earliest index where this state was seen).
        int n = s.size();

        mp["0000000000"] = -1; 

        int ans = 0;

        int cnt[10] = {};

        for(int i = 0; i<n; i++){

            cnt[s[i]-'0']++; // incrementing the count of cur_character.

            string cur_state = ""; // stores the cur_state.

            for(int j = 0; j<10; j++){

                if(cnt[j] % 2 ==0){

                    cur_state+='0';
