solutions.content:
Put the characters on top of each other on a ```stack```. And remove them off the ```stack``` when the combination with the next neighbor makes a "xX or Xx" string. Remembering the [ASCII](http://cs.smu.ca/~porter/csc/ref/ascii.html) table, the small letters and capital letters have an absolute value of "32" difference (alternatively use ```int diff = 'a'-'A'``` which sets diff to 32), thus, we can check whether the current index and neighbor make a "xX or Xx" string or not, by checking ```(st.top()==s[i+1]+32) || (st.top()==s[i+1]-32)```. 
Time: O(n)
Space: O(n)
```
class Solution {
public:
    string makeGood(string s) {
        stack<char> st;
        for (int i = 0;i<s.size();i++){
            st.push(s[i]);
            while (!st.empty() && ((st.top()==s[i+1]+32) || (st.top()==s[i+1]-32))){
                st.pop();
                i++;
            }
        }
		string ret = "";
        while(!st.empty()){
            ret = st.top() + ret;
            st.pop();
        }
        return ret;
    }
};

