# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Our task is to create a string which is good, to make a string good we need to consider
this things first
* if `last_character == curr_character` like `a, a` then append it to data structure.
* if `last_character != curr_chracter` like `(a, b) or (a, A)` then
        * check `lower(last_character) == lower(curr_character)` `(a,A)` then pop_back from data structure.
        * else append to the data structure.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
We can use deque here for sake of simplicity.
* Create a `deque of characters`.
* Iterate from start to end of the string.
* Check is `deque is empty` then simply append to it.
* else check `if(deque.back() == curr_char)` then append that character.
* else check `if(lower(deque.back()) != lower(curr_char))` then append that character.
* else pop_back from the character.
* After n iterations, create a string and append all characters of deque in it.


# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n)$$
***where `n` is the size of the string.***
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n)$$
***where `n` is the size of the string.***

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool check(char a, char b) {
        if(a == b) {
            return true;
        }
        return tolower(a) != tolower(b); 
    }

    string makeGood(string s) {
        deque<char> st;

        int n = s.length();
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if (st.empty()) {
                st.push_back(s[i]);
            }
            else if(check(st.back(), s[i])) {
                st.push_back(s[i]);
            } else {
                st.pop_back();
            }
        }

        string ans = "";
        while(!st.empty()) {
            ans.push_back(st.front());
            st.pop_front();
        }

        return ans;
    }
};
```

