solutions.content:
It could be much cleaner if we had native Stack implementation in Go, but we don't, so the solution contains some slice operation to push and pop elements.

The `isBad` function uses the idea that two characters in different registers are placed at the same distance in the ASCII table, but we have to ensure that `a` is greather than `b` in order not to overflow the `byte` type which is unsigned integer when we calculate distance between `a` and `b`.

```go
func makeGood(s string) string {
    if len(s) < 2 {
        return s
    }

    res := make([]byte, 0, len(s))
    for i := 0; i < len(s); i++ {
        last := len(res) - 1

        if len(res) == 0 || !isBad(res[last], s[i]) {
            res = append(res, s[i])
        } else {
            res = res[:last]
        }
    }

    return string(res)
}

func isBad(a, b byte) bool {
