# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Here as we have to remove adjacent characters of a string if the string is a bad string. As we have to keep the track of the previous character processed of the string along with the current character we proceed using the stack approach.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Here we use ASCII difference to compare the characters. We know ASCII value of A-Z is from 65 to 90 and ASCII value of a-z is from a-z. Here we notice that difference between any lower case character and corresponding upper case character is 32. 
(E.g : a-A => 97-65 = 32).

If the difference between the top character of the stack and the current character of the string is equal to 32, this implies we have found a pair (eE or Ee) to be removed.
We then remove the top character of the stack and move forward. This goes until we reach the end of the string and all such pairs.

At the end we run a loop on the stack and transfer all characters of the stack to the ans string variable in such a way that stack is reversed and we get the desired string,
# Complexity
- Time complexity:  O(n)
- As we are traversing the string only once , hence the time complexity of the above solution is O(n).
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n)
- As we are using a stack which in worst case may store all the characters of the string , hence the space complexity of the above approach is O(n). 

- The space complexity can be optimized to O(1) using two pointers and proceeding with a similar trend changing the string in place.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    string makeGood(string s) {
        stack<char>st;
        string ans="";
        int n=s.size();
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++) {
            if(!st.empty() && abs(s[i]-st.top())==32) // If we find a bad pair such as Aa or aA , then we remove the previous character processed
            st.pop();
            else
            st.push(s[i]); // if the stack is empty or if the pair is not a bad one.
        }

        while (!st.empty()) {
            ans = st.top() + ans;
            st.pop();
        }

        return ans; 
    }
};
```

