The first digit is always "0" regardless of `n`. The middle digit at `2**(n-1)` is always `1`. If `k < 2**(n-1)`, one could reduce the problem to `n-1` which is half the size. Otherwise, focus on the other half by reversing the position and "0"/"1". 

```
class Solution:
    def findKthBit(self, n: int, k: int) -> str:
        if k == 1: return "0"
        if k == 2**(n-1): return "1"
        if k < 2**(n-1): return self.findKthBit(n-1, k)
        return "0" if self.findKthBit(n-1, 2**n-k) == "1" else "1"
```

