solutions.content:
# Find Kth Bit in Nth Binary String
Here's a comprehensive guide to the solution.

![Screenshot 2022-12-27 171237.jpg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/72127d92-d773-444a-a6e6-807616302496_1672141365.2253892.jpeg)


## Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The idea of solving this through recursion comes fairly naturally. Considering that the constraints tell that the length number could be as large as 2^20 -- this eliminates the possibility to use string-to-long-long conversion since even iterating through one for loop with these contraints will be computationally impossible for one machine.

## Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The approach is fairly simple:
- If n==1, then return *'0'* since the start of every number is the bit *'0'*.
- if k is the middle bit of the string, return *'1'* since we concatenate two strings with *'1'* in between.
- if k is anywhere before the middle bit of the string, answer will be same as *findKthBit(n-1,k)* since k belongs to the first concatenated string (which isn't reversed).
- Else if k is a value after the middle bit, we must do some [calculations](##calculations) for k

## Calculations for last case:
First we must reduce k to the number of bits it is ahead of the middle bit. Hence 
```
=> knew = k - (2^(n))/2 
=> knew = k - 2^(n-1)
```
Now, we need to find the value of this knew when the string is reversed (remember this is the reversed string). Hence,
```
=> knew = 2^(nnew)-knew
putting values of nnew and knew, this becomes:
=> knew = 2^(n-1)-(k-2^(n-1))
=> knew = 2*2^(n-1)-k
=> knew = 2^(n)-k
```
## Complexity
- Time complexity: *O(log(n))*
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: *O(1)*
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    char findKthBit(int n, int k) {
        if(n==1){
            return '0'; 
        }
        if(pow(2,n)/k==2){
            return '1';
        }
        if(k<pow(2,n)/2){
            return findKthBit(n-1,k);
        }
        k = pow(2,n)-k;
        if(findKthBit(n-1,k)=='1'){
            return '0';
        }
        return '1';
    }
};
```

