# Intuition
Total # of characters present in string is dependent on n which is (2^n)-1 .
All characters in Sn can be divided into two parts . 
1. Those before its mid point , i.e before 2^n/2, are exactly same to Sn-1  .
2. Those after mid point are reverse of invert of Sn-1.

It forms a recursion .
For 1st , character at kth pos in Sn = char.At( kth pos in Sn-1 )
For 2nd , char.At( kth pos in Sn ) = invert of char.At( (2^n)-k th pos in Sn-1 ).
Why (2^n)-k ? 
Because we reverse Sn-1 . So gth pos in Sn , where g> mid index in Sn , is (2^n)-g th pos in Sn-1.
Few corner cases -
When k==1 , its always '0'
Whne k is mid point , its always '1'.
# Approach
We first find the lowest n required to cover k characters . It can be lesser than n . Max n steps .
Max 20 steps in recursion . log(2^n)

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
n+O(log(2^n)) ~ n

- Space complexity:
O(1)

If having doubts , feel free to comment .

# Code
```
class Solution {
    char inv(char ch){
        return (ch=='1')?'0':'1';
    }
    char rec(int k,int n){
        if(k<((int)Math.pow(2,n)/2)){
            return rec(k,n-1);
        }
        if(k==1){
            return '0';
        }
        if(n>1 && (int)Math.pow(2,n)/2==k){
            return '1';
        }
        return inv(rec((int)Math.pow(2,n)-k,n-1));

    }
    public char findKthBit(int n, int k) {
        if(k==1){
            return '0';
        }
        int l=1,v=2;
        while(v<=k){
            l++;
            v*=2;
        }
        return rec(k,l);
    }
}
```

