solutions.content:
This solution is similar to figure out any subArray with target sum. Addition thing is to find maximum such subarray. 
We can go with greedy by collecting smallest subarray with targetSum, and all such small subarray count will always be maximum.

Example to find single subArray with targetSum:
`[-2,6,6,3,5,4,1,2,8]` 
preSum array: `[-2, 4, 10, 13, 18, 22, 23, 25, 33]`

If you can store all previous seen preSum, it's easy to see if targetSum can be achieved by just checking if `preSum-target` exist in set. To store previous seen, i used hashSet.

i.e. when i = 6 (a[i] = 1, presum = 23) , i check if preSum-target (13) exist in set, since 13 already exist in set, subArray `5,4,1` can make to targetSum.

This was idea behind finding out single subArray. For maximum subarray, there are three targetSum subarray
`[-2,6,6]` 
`[5,4,1]`
`[2,8]`

That means when ever i see first targetSum array `[-2,6,6]`, i found one subArray, now imagine that i don't have my previous elements at all in array, or array is splitted in to two half.
`[-2,6,6 ||| 3,5,4,1,2,8]` -> from this point onwards i just had to search targetSum subarray in `[3,5,4,1,2,8]` array.

That means when ever i see first targetSum array `[5,4,1]`, i collect and split my input array from here
`[-2,6,6 ||| 3,5,4,1, ||| 2,8]`
Since expectation is to just collect count, everytime i just increase `ans` variable.

```
class Solution {
    public int maxNonOverlapping(int[] nums, int target) {
        int ans = 0; int preSum = 0;

        Set<Integer> set = new HashSet<>();
        set.add(0);

        for (int i = 0; i< nums.length; i++) {
            preSum += nums[i];
            if (set.contains(preSum-target)) {
				//Since we one subArray, clear all previous values to have fresh start
                set.clear(); set.add(0);  
                preSum=0;
                ans++;
            }
            set.add(preSum);
        }
        return ans;
    }
}
```

