Ideas:
1. Calculate preSum from 0 to i 
	e.g.  nums = [1,2,3],  target = 3
	```
		preSum array = [0, 1, 1+2, 1+2+3]
		preSum array = [0, 1, 3, 6]
	```
	Remenber to add the initial 0 to deal with situations where target subarray starts from first value in nums
2. target = preSum[end] - preSum[start]  -> target can be found in subarray nums[end - 1] to nums[start] 
3. We can check for a given preSum[end], whether the previous preSum array exist (target - preSum[end]). 
	If yes, we found a subarray.
4. To avoid overlapping subarray:
	Once we found a subarray, we need to start looking from current index.

Optimize:
Here, index doesn't really matters. We can use a hashSet as the previous mentioned preSum array. We only need to make sure that once we found a subarray, we reset the hashSet to avoid overlaping arrays.
```
class Solution {
    public int maxNonOverlapping(int[] nums, int target) {
        HashSet<Integer> preSum = new HashSet<>();
        preSum.add(0);
        int sum = 0;
        int count = 0;

        for(int n: nums){
            sum += n;
            if(preSum.contains(sum - target)){
                count ++;
                preSum = new HashSet<>();
            }
            preSum.add(sum);
        }
        return count;
    }
}
