solutions.content:
The core idea is: **by storing all prefix sum inside hashmap, we can find whether there exists a subarray till now that sums to target**. 

For example, prefix sum for `[2,3,1]` is `[2,5,6]`, and suppose the target is `4` and we are at the third position. Then. **we only need to find whether the hashmap contains `2 = (6 - 4)`**. If so, starting from index `1` till `2`, `[3,1]` is a valid subarray.

Thus, we can do this greedily starting from beginning to end of the array. Once we find a valid subarray, plus one to the final result, and clear all previous records - since no overlapping is allowed. We continue such process on the following array till the end of the array.

Eventually, we'll get the final result.

**Beats 99.58% int time and 80.08% in space**
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/b115b316-31ad-41f6-b625-318caa60537b_1662450520.7427568.jpeg)

```
class Solution {
public:
    int maxNonOverlapping(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
        unordered_map<int, int> m; // map that stores prefix sums
        m[0] = -1;  // 0 for full-length subarray
        int currSum = 0, res = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {
            currSum += nums[i];
            if (m.find(currSum - target) != m.end()) { // check if there exists a valid subarray
                res++;
                m.clear(); // discard all previous info
                m[0] = i; // 0 for full-length subarray
                currSum = 0; // reset currSum
            } else { // if not, keep recording infos
                m[currSum] = i;
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

