solutions.content:
First of all, because we need to solve for all possibilities of order, ie., the most optimal, the order in which we explore those cuts won't matter at all. 
And in situations wherein order of the input doesn't matter, the strategy used is to first sort the input in ascending or descending order depending on the particular use case that we are looking for. In this case, I have sorted in ascending order.

Now, beware, there are two different things in this problem. 

The *first one* is the ***cuts array*** which tells us **the places where we need to do the respective cuts** and, *the second* is the ***entire rod*** on which **the cut operations would be performed**.

The value ***n*** is the length of the rod and ***NOT*** the length of the ***cuts*** array. 
This mere observation that I overlooked took me a lot of time to figure out the problem properly.

*Rest is pretty easy.*

```
for(int i=idx; i<=jdx; i++){
            int left = fun(cuts, idx,i-1, l, cuts[i],dp) ;
            int right = fun(cuts, i+1,jdx, cuts[i],r,dp);
            ans = min(ans,r-l+left+right);
        }
```
So, the above snippet is the main gist of the entire code. 
First, let's clarify the variables in the **fun** function.

* idx is the left index that we need to deal with in the cuts array
* jdx is the right index that we need to deal with in the cuts array.
* l and r are left end and the right ends of the rods at any given recursive call

Simply iterating over the cuts array and making cuts at every instance and correspondingly changing the end position of the cut portion that we have to do depending on the values passed over by previous recursive calls.

For left call at a particular cut ***i***, we need to start the left portion from the ***idx*** (the corresponding beginning part of that cut in that recursive call) to ***i-1*** which is just before the cut. This handles the **cuts** array, 

To handle the rod, we need to specify just the remaining part of the array where the starting and ending point of the rod must be.

Similarly for the right part.
And we need to simply add values we obtain from right and left recursion calls and add the corresponding rod length for that recursive call ie., l-r.

That's it.


```
class Solution {
public:
    int fun(vector<int> &cuts, int idx, int jdx, int l, int r,vector<vector<int>>&dp){
        if(idx<0 || jdx>=cuts.size()||idx>jdx){
            return 0;
        }
        if(idx==jdx){
            return r-l;
        }
        if(dp[idx][jdx]!=-1){
            return dp[idx][jdx];
        }
        int ans = 1e9;
        for(int i=idx; i<=jdx; i++){
            int left = fun(cuts, idx,i-1, l, cuts[i],dp) ;
            int right = fun(cuts, i+1,jdx, cuts[i],r,dp);
            ans = min(ans,r-l+left+right);
        }
        return dp[idx][jdx] = ans;
    }
    int minCost(int n, vector<int>& cuts) {
        sort(cuts.begin(),cuts.end());
        int x = cuts.size();
        vector<vector<int>> dp(x,vector<int>(x,-1));
        return fun(cuts,0,cuts.size()-1,0,n,dp);
    }
};
```

