solutions.content:
**Note:** At first, I couldn't understand why everyone is sorting the cuts or adding 0 and n to the cuts array. It took me some time to understand why everyone is doing that actually. 
Please go through the entire explanation and codes to understand more clearly 

**Case 1:** **Implementing without sorting and without adding 0 or n to the cuts** **(TLE)**
* This is same as implementing top down approach for any other problem.
* We try to peform cut at every possible index, if the cut position is in the starting and ending range of stick.
* Sometimes we cannot peform cut because it might be outside of the stick range.
	* **Ex:** Suppose, for a stick of **length 6** with the starting and ending pos of stick currently being [2,5]. We cannot perform cuts which are <=2 and >=5 as they lies outside of the current stick range.
	* We skip these cuts and do not peform on the current stick.

```
class Solution {
public:

	// Creating a 2-D array of size 1000001 x c, where c is some random value
	unordered_map<int, int> dp[1000001];

    int topDown(int stickStart, int stickEnd, vector<int> &cuts){
		// Not possible case
        if(stickStart >= stickEnd){
            return 0;
        }

        if(dp[stickStart].find(stickEnd) != dp[stickStart].end()){
			return dp[stickStart][stickEnd];
		}

        int ans = INT_MAX;

		// We try to peform cuts at every possible position
        for(int k=0; k<cuts.size(); k++){
			// The cut is not possible, as it is not present in starting and ending range of stick
            if(cuts[k] <= stickStart || cuts[k] >= stickEnd){
                continue;
            }
            int l = topDown(stickStart, cuts[k], cuts);
            int r = topDown(cuts[k], stickEnd, cuts);
			int len = stickEnd - stickStart;
            ans = min(ans, l+r+len);
        }
        return dp[i][j] = (ans == INT_MAX ? 0 : ans);
    }

    int minCost(int n, vector<int>& cuts) {
        return topDown(0, n, 0, size(cuts)-1, cuts);
    }
};
```

**Note:** The problem with above approach is we're **iterating the cuts array no matter what the starting and ending ranges of the stick are** and only performing cut in cases where it is possible.

Thus, we are unnecessarily checking all cuts, which becomes an overhead. So, we sort  the cuts array and pass the cuts which are only possible in that stick range. 

**Case 2:** **Using sorting:** **(Accepted)**
* In this case, we pass the cutsStart and cutsEnd representing starting and ending indices of the cuts that are possible on the current stick starting at **stickStart** and ending at **stickEnd**.

```
class Solution {
public:

    int dp[101][101];

    int topDown(int stickStart, int stickEnd, int cutsStart, int cutsEnd, vector<int> &cuts){
        if(cutsStart > cutsEnd){
            return 0;
        }

        if(dp[cutsStart][cutsEnd] != -1)
            return dp[cutsStart][cutsEnd];

        int ans = INT_MAX;

		// Iterating over only possible cuts
        for(int k=cutsStart; k<=cutsEnd; k++){

			// All the cuts which lies >=k are useless for the left stick subproblem
            int l = topDown(stickStart, cuts[k], cutsStart, k-1, cuts);

			// All the cuts which lies <=k are useless for the right stick subproblem
            int r = topDown(cuts[k], stickEnd, k+1, cutsEnd, cuts);

            int len = stickEnd - stickStart;
            ans = min(ans, l+r+len);
        }

        return dp[cutsStart][cutsEnd] = (ans == INT_MAX ? 0 : ans);
    }

    int minCost(int n, vector<int>& cuts) {
        memset(dp, -1, sizeof(dp));
        sort(begin(cuts), end(cuts));
        return topDown(0, n, 0, size(cuts)-1, cuts);
    }
};
```
