solutions.content:
This is indeed a very challenging question. I will do my best to explain my attempt at solving this. 

There are already some great posts on DFS + Memo. Please read up on some if you aren't familiar.

Bottom Up:
Take example n = 7, cuts = [1,3,4,5]
Basically, redefining the larger problem **what is the minimum cost of cutting the stick from (0, 6) by applying all cuts** defined as f(0,6)
Still confusing... Lets break apart of the problem. 
What is the minimum cost of cutting the stick from (0, 1) by applying all cuts **plus** the minimum cost of cutting the stick from (1, 6) by applying all the cuts. 
*Basically split the (0,6) into (0,1)+(1,6), (0,3)+(3,6) and so forth.*

Now we can break this into a equation:
`f(0,6) = min(f(0,1) + f(1,6), f(0,3) + f(3,6), f(0,4) + f(4,6), f(0,5) + f(5,6)) + (6-0)  // add the distance from 0 to 6`
Taking the first `f(0,1) + f(1,6)`
`f(0,1) = 0, we can't cut from f(0,1)`
`f(1,6) = min(f(0,3) + f(3,6), f(0,4) + f(4,6),  f(0,5) + f(5,6)) + (6 - 1)`
Taking the first `f(0,3) + f(3,6)`
`f(0,3) = 0 we can't cut from f(0,3)`
`f(3,6) = min(f(3,4) + f(4,6), f(3,5) + f(5,6)) + (6-3)`
`f(3,4) = 0, we can't cut from f(3,4)`
`f(4,6) = min(f(4,5) + f(5,6)) + (6 - 4)`
`f(4,5), f(5,6) = 0`

Notice that since `dp[i][j]` requires `dp[i+1][ j-1]`. We need to loop like 
```
for (i=n -> 0)
	for (j=i+1 -> n)
	for (cut : cuts) 
	  if (cut > i && cut < j) // this is necessary so we don't count (0,3) or (3,5) with cut = 3 as cuttable 
```

```
class Solution {
    public int minCost(int n, int[] cuts) {
        int[][] dp = new int[n+1][n+1];

        for (int i = n; i >= 0; i--) {
            for (int j = i+1; j <= n; j++) {
                int dist = j-i;
                int min = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
                for (int cut : cuts) {
                    if (cut > i && cut < j) {
                        min = Math.min(min, dp[i][cut] + dp[cut][j]);
                    }
                }
                if (min != Integer.MAX_VALUE) {
                    dp[i][j] = min + dist;
                }
            }
        }
        return dp[0][n];
    }
}
```
N = cuts.length
M = n
Time: **O(M2 * N)**
Space: **O(M2)**

This solution will eventually run into a **TLE** :( because we are looping through **0 to n**

To Optimize,
Remember that if n = 100000 and cut is 5. We know that any value from `dp[0][0]` to `dp[0][4]` and `dp[0][6]` to `dp[0][100000]` are going to be the same.
This is great waste of space and time. We can optimze this by only **focusing on the cutting points.** 
Recall that our dp solutions work by `dp[start][end]` without the leftmost, rightmost bound we will be cutting the board only from 1 to 5 in `cuts=[1,3,4,5]`

```
class Solution {
    public int minCost(int n, int[] cuts) {
        int[][] dp = new int[cuts.length+2][cuts.length+2];
        List<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();
        Arrays.sort(cuts);
        list.add(0);
        for (int i = 0; i < cuts.length; i++) {
            list.add(cuts[i]);
        }
        list.add(n);

        for (int i = list.size()-1; i >= 0; i--) {
            for (int j = i+1; j < list.size(); j++) {
                int dist = list.get(j) - list.get(i);
                int min = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
                for (int index = 0; index < list.size(); index++) { 
                    int cut = list.get(index);
                    if (cut > list.get(i) && cut < list.get(j)) {
                        min = Math.min(min, dp[i][index] + dp[index][j]);
                    }
                }
                if (min != Integer.MAX_VALUE) {
                    dp[i][j] = min + dist;
                }
            }
        }

        return dp[0][cuts.length+1];
    }
}
```
N = cuts.length
Time: O(N lg N) + O(N3) so **O(N3)**
Space: **O(N2)**

Finally, last optimization here
Notice that in the third for loop where we scan through the **entire** list to find an index that is great than list.get(i)
We can narrow this search by finding the insertion point by using binary search (notice worst case remains the same but the average case will be better)

```
class Solution {
    public int minCost(int n, int[] cuts) {
        int[][] dp = new int[cuts.length+2][cuts.length+2];
        List<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();
        Arrays.sort(cuts);
        list.add(0);
        for (int i = 0; i < cuts.length; i++) {
            list.add(cuts[i]);

        }
        list.add(n);

        for (int i = list.size()-1; i >= 0; i--) {
            for (int j = i+1; j < list.size(); j++) {
                int dist = list.get(j) - list.get(i);
                int min = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
                // System.out.println(i + " " + index);
                int lo = 0;
                int hi = list.size()-1;
                while (lo < hi) {
                    int mid = lo + (hi - lo)/2;
                    if (list.get(mid) > list.get(i)) {
                        hi = mid;
                    }
                    else {
                        lo = mid + 1;
                    }
                }
                while (lo < list.size() && list.get(lo) < list.get(j)) {
                    int cut = list.get(lo);
                    if (cut > list.get(i) && cut < list.get(j)) {
                        min = Math.min(min, dp[i][lo] + dp[lo][j]);
                    }
                    lo++;
                }

                if (min != Integer.MAX_VALUE) {
                    dp[i][j] = min + dist;
                }
            }
        }
        return dp[0][cuts.length+1];
    }
}
```
N = cuts.length
Time: O(N lg N) + O(N2 * N) so **O(N3)**
Space: **O(N2)**

