# Intuition
The idea is to divide the stick into smaller sub-sticks and recursively calculate the minimum cost for each sub-stick.

# Approach
Use memoization to store previously computed results and avoid redundant calculations.

1. Check if the minimum cost for the range (i, j) is already present in mem. If found, return the stored value.
2. Iterate through the cuts.
3. If the cut[k] position is less than or equal to the left index i, we can't cut with this so skip to the next iteration.
4. If the current cut position is greater than or equal to the ending index j, break out of the loop. Array is sorted therefor next cuts will always be out of range.
5. Add current cost that is length of substick j-i and recursively calculate the cost for the left and right sub-ranges from cut.
6. Update the minimum cost in mem based on the calculated cost.
7. If no cuts have been made in the current range (i, j), return 0, That means all the cuts have been made.
8. Return the minimum cost stored in mem for the range (i, j).

- sort the cuts array 

# Code
```C++
class Solution {
public:
    int n;
    map<pair<int, int>, int> mem;

    int rec(int i, int j, vector<int> &cuts){
        if(mem.find({i, j}) != mem.end()) return mem[{i, j}];

        bool flag = false;
        for(int k = 0; k<cuts.size(); k++){
            if(cuts[k] <= i) continue;
            if(cuts[k] >= j) break;

            if(!flag){ // if mem[{i, j}] is not initialized
                mem[{i, j}] = j-i + rec(i, cuts[k], cuts)+rec(cuts[k], j, cuts);
            } else {
                mem[{i, j}] = min(mem[{i, j}], j-i + rec(i, cuts[k], cuts)+rec(cuts[k], j, cuts));
            } 
            flag = true;
        }

        if(!flag) return 0;
        return mem[{i, j}];
    }

    int minCost(int z, vector<int>& cuts) {
        n = z;
        sort(cuts.begin(), cuts.end());

        return rec(0, n, cuts);
    }
};
```

