# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The intuition behind the solution is to use dynamic programming to find the minimum cost of the cuts.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Create a new array newCuts with the starting and ending points of the stick, and sort it in ascending order.
1. Initialize a 2D array dp to store the minimum costs for different segments of the stick.
1. Iterate through different lengths of segments and calculate the minimum cost by considering different cut positions within each segment.
1. Return the minimum cost stored in dp[0][newCuts.length - 1].

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The time complexity of the solution is O(n^3), where n is the length of the newCuts array. The nested loops contribute to this complexity.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The space complexity of the solution is O(n^2) because of the dp array, which has dimensions of newCuts.length by newCuts.length.

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int minCost(int n, int[] cuts) {
        int[] newCuts = new int[cuts.length + 2];
        newCuts[0] = 0;
        newCuts[newCuts.length - 1] = n;
        System.arraycopy(cuts, 0, newCuts, 1, cuts.length);
        Arrays.sort(newCuts);

        int[][] dp = new int[newCuts.length][newCuts.length];
        for (int len = 2; len < newCuts.length; len++) {
            for (int i = 0; i + len < newCuts.length; i++) {
                int j = i + len;
                dp[i][j] = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
                for (int k = i + 1; k < j; k++) {
                    dp[i][j] = Math.min(dp[i][j], dp[i][k] + dp[k][j] + newCuts[j] - newCuts[i]);
                }
            }
        }

        return dp[0][newCuts.length - 1];
    }
}
```

