solutions.content:
We have a stick of length N and can make cuts only where we are allowed. Now the cost of cutting a stick is equal to its length. 
ex Example 1:

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/d86ef826-eae3-4acf-ad5c-7b40d55d802f_1630423796.4006917.png)

Input: n = 7, cuts = [1,3,4,5]
Output: 16
Explanation: Using cuts order = [1, 3, 4, 5] as in the input leads to the following scenario:
The first cut is done to a rod of length 7 so the cost is 7. The second cut is done to a rod of length 6 (i.e. the second part of the first cut), the third is done to a rod of length 4 and the last cut is to a rod of length 3. The total cost is 7 + 6 + 4 + 3 = 20.
Rearranging the cuts to be [3, 5, 1, 4] for example will lead to a scenario with total cost = 16 (as shown in the example photo 7 + 4 + 3 + 2 = 16).

## Recusive Approach

### Base Case
If we a cut the rod and end up with a peice which has a stating index si and ending index ei . Like in our example 1 , when we reach a point at which the startig index =  1 and ending index of rod peice is 3 ,(second peice in the end) , we are not allowed to cut the rod anywhere in this range , hence here our answer should be 0.

### Hypothesis 

**Our Job is to just divide the rod into two peices and let recursion handle the rest.**
So if we have a rod peice with starting index si and index ei , then we try to divide the rod into 2 peice , by cutting it at any of the given points and get the ans , see which is two division , guve the minimun sum of cuts.
Ex . when we have starting index = and ending index is 7 , we need to check all places where we can it . 
* Case 1 , cut it at length 1. case1 = minWays(0,1) + minWays(1,7)
* Case 2 , cut it at length 3, case2 = minWays(0,3) + minWays (3,7).
* Case 3 , cut it at length 4 , case3 = minWays(0,4) + minWays(4,7).
* Case 4 , cut it at length 5 , case4 = minWays(0,5) + minWays(5,7).

### Induction Step

Now we take the minmum of these 4 and add our length to it

Our answer = (7-0) + min(case1 , case2 , case3 , case4)

### Coding for Recursive Approach + Adding Memoizsation

So , we cant really cut this road at any places instead of the places given , so we add 0 and length of rod to the given cuts array and sort it.
Although we pass the indexes of the array , these can handle the rod cuts and length .
because evntually any final rod element left  will have si and ei from the cuts array.

When we start building the recusion tree we see that there are a lot of overlapping subproblems .

Ex
* in case1 minCost(0,7) if cut at 1 first , will call , minCost(0,1) and minCost(1,7).
* mincost(1,7) will difenitely hit minCost(1,3) , minCost(3,7) and these will further call minCost(3,4) , minCost(4,7) ans so on.
* When we calculate for case2 a cut at 3 , it will again at some make these calls and there will be subroblems. (Draw recursion tree)

Hence we create a dp and use a memoization solution to store our answer and reach at the below given Top-Down Approach.


```

    int minCostMemo(int n , vector<int>& cuts , int dp[103][103] ,int si , int ei ){

        if((ei-si)<=1){
            return 0;
        }

        if(dp[si][ei]!=-1){
            return dp[si][ei];
        }
        int smallAns =  INT_MAX;
        for(int i = si+1 ; i < ei ; i++){
            int p1 =  minCostMemo(n,cuts,dp,si,i);
            int p2 =  minCostMemo(n,cuts,dp,i,ei);
            smallAns = min(p1+p2 , smallAns);
        }
        int myAns = smallAns +  cuts[ei]-cuts[si];
        dp[si][ei] = myAns ;
        return myAns;

    }

    int minCost(int n, vector<int>& cuts) {

        int minCutIndex = INT_MAX;
        int maxCutIndex = INT_MIN;
        vector<int> cutsIndex;
        for(int i = 0 ; i  < cuts.size() ; i++){
            minCutIndex=min(minCutIndex,cuts[i]);
            maxCutIndex=max(maxCutIndex,cuts[i]);
            cutsIndex.push_back(cuts[i]);
        }

        if(minCutIndex != 0){
            cutsIndex.push_back(0);
        }
        if(maxCutIndex != n){
            cutsIndex.push_back(n);
        }

        sort(cutsIndex.begin(), cutsIndex.end());
        int N = cutsIndex.size();
        int dp[103][103];
        for(int i = 0 ; i<N ; i++ ){
            for(int j = 0 ; j <N ; j++){
                dp[i][j] = -1;
            }
        }

        int ans = minCostMemo(N,  cutsIndex , dp , 0 , N-1);


        return ans;      
    }


```

## Dynamic Programming (Bottom-Up)

Now We see  that at the end , we stop when there are 0 cuts between the starting and ending points  , answer will be 0 . We calculate answers for cases where the the number of cuts between the starting index and eding index of rod peice is 1 , then when we calclate the ans for the cases where gap between startinga and ending peices is 2 , we will depend on precomputed answer and, we fill our DP matrix  diagonally .

dp[i][j] stores the min cost of cutting we cut  the rod starting from length cutsIndxes[i] and cutsIndex[j]

 ```
int minCost(int n, vector<int>& cuts) {

	int minCutIndex = INT_MAX;
	int maxCutIndex = INT_MIN;
	vector<int> cutsIndex;
	for(int i = 0 ; i  < cuts.size() ; i++){
		minCutIndex=min(minCutIndex,cuts[i]);
		maxCutIndex=max(maxCutIndex,cuts[i]);
		cutsIndex.push_back(cuts[i]);
	}

	if(minCutIndex != 0){
		cutsIndex.push_back(0);
	}
	if(maxCutIndex != n){
		cutsIndex.push_back(n);
	}

	sort(cutsIndex.begin(), cutsIndex.end());
	int N = cutsIndex.size();
	int dp[103][103];
	for(int i = 0 ; i<N ; i++ ){
		for(int j = 0 ; j <N ; j++){
			dp[i][j] = 0;
		}
	}

	for(int gap = 2 ;  gap < N ; gap++){
		for(int i =0,j=gap ; i <N &&j<N ; i++,j++){
			int ans =INT_MAX;
			for(int k = i+1 ; k<j ;k++){
				ans=min(ans,dp[i][k] + dp[k][j]);
			}
			dp[i][j] = ans+cutsIndex[j]-cutsIndex[i] ;
		}
	}

	// int ans = minCostMemo(N,  cutsIndex , dp , 0 , N-1);
	int ans = dp[0][N-1];

	return ans;      
}
