solutions.content:
These problems are very similar: 

* [312. Burst Balloons](https://leetcode.com/problems/burst-balloons/discuss/1242141/Java-clean-O(N3)-DP-Solution-oror-with-comments)
* [1547. Minimum Cost to Cut a Stick](https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-cost-to-cut-a-stick/discuss/1242108/Java-Two-Clean-O(N3)-Solution)

For me, Solution 1 is actually more natural. Coming from the brute force way, it just optimized a little bit by storing sub-results to avoid repeated queries. However, Solution 2 with DP in real practice runs faster because of the subseting in Solution 1. 

**Solution 1:**
```
class Solution {
    private TreeSet<Integer> set = new TreeSet<>();
    private int n;

    private Map<Integer, Integer> memo = new HashMap<>();

    public int minCost(int n, int[] cuts) {
        for (int c : cuts) set.add(c);
        this.n = n;

        return helper(0, n);
    }

    private int helper(int i, int j) {
        int key = i * (n+1) + j;
        if (memo.containsKey(key)) return memo.get(key);

        int res = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        for (int c : set.subSet(i, false, j, false)) {
            res = Math.min(res, (j - i) + helper(i, c) + helper(c, j));
        }

        if (res == Integer.MAX_VALUE) res = 0;
        memo.put(key, res);

        return res;
    }
}
```

**Solution 2:**
```
class Solution {
    public int minCost(int n, int[] cuts) {
        int len = cuts.length + 2;

        int[] endpoints = new int[len];
        endpoints[0] = 0;
        for (int i = 1; i < len - 1; i++) endpoints[i] = cuts[i-1];
        endpoints[len - 1] = n;
        Arrays.sort(endpoints);


        int[][] dp = new int[len][len];

        // d : dist between i & j, the starting & ending position of stick 
        for (int d = 2; d < len; d++) {
            for (int i = 0, j = i + d; j < len; i++, j++) {
                dp[i][j] = Integer.MAX_VALUE;

                int curr = endpoints[j] - endpoints[i];
                for (int k = i + 1; k < j; k++) {
                    dp[i][j] = Math.min(dp[i][j], dp[i][k] + dp[k][j] + curr);
                }
            }
        }
        return dp[0][len - 1];
    }
}
```

